Lecture 3: Human Rights, Diversity & Inclusion. Human rights are moral principles or norms for certain standards of human behavior and are protected as natural and legal rights. The Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) was adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948. Diversity refers to the range of human differences, including race, ethnicity, gender, age, social class, and physical ability. Inclusion is the practice of providing equal access to opportunities and resources for people who might otherwise be excluded or marginalized.